1 5. Garnishing, attaching or seizing, or threatening to garnish, attach or
2 seize, a bank account of a consumer.
3 Sec. 15. 1. A health care entity or collection agency shall not engage in
4 any extraordinary collection action until at least 180 days after the first bill for a
5 medical debt has been sent to a consumer.
6 2. At least 30 days before taking any extraordinary collection action to
7 collect a medical debt, a health care entity or collection agency shall provide to
8 the consumer a notice:
9 (a) Identifying the extraordinary collection action that will be initiated in
10 order to obtain payment;
11 (b) Providing a deadline after which such extraordinary collection action
12 will be initiated, which must be not earlier than 30 days after the date of the
13 notice; and
14 (c) If the medical debt was incurred for medical services, medical products or
15 medical devices provided by a medical facility, stating whether the medical facility
16 offers financial assistance to eligible consumers and providing a plain-language
17 summary of any financial assistance policy of the medical facility.
18 3. A health care entity or collection agency shall not engage in any
19 extraordinary collection action against a consumer for a medical debt during any
20 period in which, in any part of the county in this State in which the consumer
21 resides, there exists:
22 (a) A state of emergency or declaration of disaster proclaimed pursuant to
23 NRS 414.070;
24 (b) A public health emergency or other health event pursuant to NRS
25 439.970; or
26 (c) A state of emergency, declaration of disaster or public health emergency
27 as declared pursuant to federal law [or the laws of another state.] which has been
28 in effect for less than 6 months.
29 4. Any statute of limitations applicable to a claim to recover on a medical
30 debt shall be tolled during any period in which a health care entity or collection
31 agency is prohibited from engaging in any extraordinary collection action
32 pursuant to subsection 3.
33 Sec. 16. 1. If a medical debt was incurred for medical services, medical
34 products or medical devices provided by a health care entity, the health care
35 entity or a collection agency shall not engage in any extraordinary collection
36 action to recover the medical debt unless such extraordinary collection action is
37 described in the billing and collections policy of the health care entity.
38 2. If a health care entity, or a collection agency acting to collect a medical
39 debt incurred for medical services, medical products or medical devices provided
40 by a health care entity, initiates an extraordinary collection action against a
41 consumer to collect a medical debt and the consumer is later found to be eligible
42 under the financial assistance policy of the health care entity for financial
43 assistance that eliminates or would have eliminated the medical debt, the health
44 care entity or collection agency shall reverse any such extraordinary collection
45 action, including, without limitation, removing any lien, attachment or
46 garnishment against the property of the consumer.
47 3. If, after the application of any financial assistance for which a consumer
48 is eligible, the consumer has paid, to a health care entity, a collection agency or
49 both, an amount in excess of the amount of the medical debt, the health care
50 entity or collection agency shall refund any excess amount to the consumer
51 within 60 days.
52 Sec. 17. The protections set forth in sections 13 to 16, inclusive, of this act
53 are for the benefit of consumers and cannot be waived.

